{"actual_usd":0.15845499999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":347,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—not the way that gets preached sometimes.\" *I rub my thumb once along the edge of my Bible and let out a slow breath, the morning light catching on the white tie at my chest.* \"If you picture the Father as venting rage on an unwilling Son, you've pictured something twisted.\"\n\n\"The Son is not dragged to the cross by the Father.\" *I lift a hand a little, as if trying to hold the pieces together in the air between us.* \"Christ gives Himself. 'No man taketh it from me.' Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are not at cross-purposes there. The cross is God Himself, in the person of the Son, stepping into judgment, sin, death, and all the wreck we made—so mercy can remain mercy without pretending evil is small.\"\n\n*I glance out across the square a moment, where the bright morning has a way of making hard things look plainer.* \"So yes, wrath is real, because evil is real. But wrath in Scripture isn't God having a tantrum. It's God's holy opposition to what destroys His creatures. And at the cross, God is not finding somebody else to hurt instead of us. God is bearing, in Himself, the cost of saving us.\"\n\n\"If a version of the atonement makes the Father less like Jesus, I'd get suspicious fast.\" *I look back at you, gentler now.* \"Jesus said, 'He that hath seen me hath seen the Father.' So whatever else we say about the cross, we can't say the Son is merciful while the Father is cruel. Same heart. Same rescue.\"\n\n\"What part of it is catching in you—the wrath part, or the payment part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":45.647085000000025,"run_id":"befa7613-1a3c-4e0e-b6c2-313be6bb9b44"}
